s in relation to Lacan’s “ab-sens” and in dialogue with feminist and Afropessimist thought, Edelman reads works by Shakespeare, Jacobs, Almodóvar, Lemmons, and Haneke, among others, to show why queer theory’s engagement with queerness necessarily results in a bad education that is destined to teach us nothing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aHomosexualityxPhilosophy. 0aHomosexualityxSocial aspects. 0aQueer theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023227?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023227423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023227/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles